{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647223"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18234"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18234"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10948"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10948"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65406"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome occurs when the median nerve is compressed as it travels through the carpal tunnel at the wrist. While many cases are idiopathic, several systemic conditions can increase the risk of developing this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following systemic conditions is most commonly associated with carpal tunnel syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acromegaly","Diabetes mellitus","Hypothyroidism","Rheumatoid arthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is the systemic condition most commonly associated with carpal tunnel syndrome. The inflammatory process causes synovitis and tenosynovitis within the carpal tunnel, leading to compression of the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcromegaly\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can cause carpal tunnel syndrome through soft tissue overgrowth, it is a rare condition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E - Can cause carpal tunnel syndrome through metabolic changes but is less common than rheumatoid arthritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E - Associated with carpal tunnel syndrome due to mucopolysaccharide deposition but is less common\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E - Can cause carpal tunnel syndrome but is less common than rheumatoid arthritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther common associations include pregnancy, obesity, and occupational factors involving repetitive wrist movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Carpal tunnel syndrome is most commonly idiopathic or related to repetitive movements, with rheumatoid arthritis being the most common systemic disease association.","The median nerve can be compressed in the carpal tunnel due to inflammation, fluid retention, or structural changes.","Common risk factors include obesity, pregnancy, diabetes, and hypothyroidism."],"references":["Genova A, Dix O, Saefan A, Thakur M, Hassan A. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome: A Review of Literature. Cureus. 2020 Mar 19;12(3):e7333. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7333. PMID: 32313774; PMCID: PMC7164699","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65406"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18234"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65406"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T16:28:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T16:30:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10948"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80129"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{